{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504670"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:18:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:18:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2354"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583239"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:09:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:09:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2354"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2354"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.08,0.03,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2354"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31103"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2354"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2354"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16979"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6034"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1386"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31103"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a painful left wrist. Earlier that afternoon she fell onto the floor with an outstretched hand as she lost balance standing on a stool while cleaning her window. She did not lose consciousness before and after the fall. She did not sustain any head injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears in distress and her vital signs are stable. Her left wrist is tender to palpate and there is a slight dorsal angulated deformity. There is no open fractures or loss of skin integrity. There is a reduced range of motion on all wrist motion limited by pain. She has no snuffbox tenderness and she is able to move her fingers. Her neurovascular status is intact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn X-ray of the left wrist was performed which shows the following (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colles fracture","Smith fracture","Scaphoid fracture","Monteggia fracture","Galeazzi fracture"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient suffers from a dorsally angulated distal radius fracture, also known as a \u003Cstrong\u003EColles fracture\u003C/strong\u003E. The most common mechanism of injury is from a fall on an outstretched hands with a pronated forearm. This results in an axial force from the proximal carpal bones to the distal radius in the dorsal direction along the long axis of the radius. This axial force may lead to a dorsally angulated radial fracture.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical examination of a Colles fracture may reveal wrist pain and swelling with an associated dorsally angulated deformity. Range of motion may be limited by pain. X-rays are useful with the recommended AP, lateral and oblique views. X-ray findings may include a transverse fracture of the distal radius with dorsal angulation and displacement of the wrist and/or shortening of the ulnocarpal space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of a Colles fracture largely depends on the stability of the affected area and the severity of the fracture. Conservative treatment involves closed reduction while applying longitudinal traction with dorsal forearm splint/casting for several weeks. If the wrist is significantly displaced, intra-articular, unstable or an open fracture, surgical management is necessary which would involve an open reduction and internal fixation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EScaphoid fracture is the fracture of the scaphoid bone. The mechanism of injury is similar to a Colles fracture \u2013 a fall with an outstretched hand. It is important to rule out a scaphoid fracture in a wrist trauma/injury. Palpation of the anatomical snuffbox is necessary as tenderness in that region would indicate a scaphoid fracture. An x-ray of the scaphoid bone, in particular, a scaphoid view is necessary as this fracture may lead to avascular necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESmith fracture is the fracture of the distal radius with associated volar angulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMonteggia fracture is the fracture of the proximal ulna with associated dislocation of the radial head, while a Galeazzi fracture is the fracture of the distal radial shaft with disruption of the distal radioulnar joint.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A dorsally angulated distal radius fracture is the commonest type of fracture that may occur after a fall on to the hand."],"references":["Cooney WP 3rd, Dobyns JH, Linscheid RL. Complications of Colles\u0027 fractures. J Bone Joint Surg Am 1980; 62:613.","Lawson GM, Hajducka C, McQueen MM. Sports fractures of the distal radius--epidemiology and outcome. Injury 1995; 26:33."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16979"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2354"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18651"}]},"explanationMedi